	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Help</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Sorry for the cryptic title.<br />
<br />
I have a dilemma, and would like to solicit some opinions.<br />
<br />
I recently got a promotion, one I have been waiting quite some time for.  It was exactly what I was hoping for, with one exception:  the raise was lacking.<br />
<br />
Now rationally, I would think that when you promote someone from hourly to salary, you look at the job they currently do, the hours worked and expected in the future, and make sure that a decent amount of OT is covered in the initial raise.  It would be silly to give someone a &quot;promotion,&quot; but in practice pay them less.  But that's what happened to me.  The raise I got was worth about 2 hours per week of overtime, but I averaged double that in 2004, and that was with some significant periods of downtime with no OT at all.   Jan and Feb are busy months, but I can see my longterm workload still increasing, and see little chance that I'll actually work <i>less</i> next year.  In fact I don't really want to work less, I do like my job, and more work generally means better job security.<br />
<br />
Anyway, that's a rant for another time.  The background is necessary for my question, though.  I've submitted a few resumes in the past year, but most of them were either dream jobs or local jobs and nothing ever came fo them.  I was content with the expectation that this promotion was coming and wasn't going to waste too much energy searching for jobs.<br />
<br />
Now though, the promotion was a letdown and I've heard through an associate about a position that would pay significantly better, something like 50% better.  I am of course going to apply, but I have two questions.<br />
<br />
1.  In an interview, how should I answer a question about why I want to leave my current company?  The promotion is on my resume, but I think it might look strange me applying for something new this soon after.  The truth is that I don't <i>really</i> want to leave, and my current employer wouldn't have to match the opposing offer to keep me.  (but they'd have to do better than a fucking cut disguised as a promotion).<br />
<br />
2.  In the event that I am offered the new position, how or at what point do you think I should tell my current employer that I'm planning to leave?  Should I just give my notice and say nothing?  Or give notice and a polite version of &quot;here's why I'm upset, you have X weeks to fix this or I am leaving.&quot;  Or, would it be better to bring the concerns first, without a hint that I might leave?  So far, I have basically never complained about anything, and the one time I did they reacted instantly.  The second option seems less likely to be effective, however it's a less offensive method that would be less likely to permanently damage relationships.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
		<img class="inlineimg" src="images/statusicon/user_offline.gif" alt="Goladus is offline" border="0" />


		
		
		
		&nbsp;
	</td>
