	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				In an interview, how should I answer a question about why I want to leave my current company?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
I was hoping the promotion would renew my interest in Acme Labs but it hasn't and I'm looking for a more challenging and rewarding position.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				my current employer wouldn't have to match the opposing offer to keep me.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
The odds of things working out in the long term when you tell your boss that I don't think I'm getting paid enough, Widgets Inc. doesn't think so either how much are you willing to pay me to stop from me taking this job offer are incredibly slim.  (S)He'll never know for sure that you're not still looking for another job just to leverage even higher pay and (s)he would be &quot;best&quot; off planning for your replacement and once (s)he has that rep ready the workplace environment will suck badly.<br />
<br />
Ask for a raise, now if you're not going to last until April, don't mention any other job or even looking, talk about wanting to have your girlfriend and her 2 kids move out of her parent's house and how a raise would really help, talk about your mother's medical bills or just be honest and say that you feel you deserve it.  Mentioning another job when asking for a raise is only slightly better in the long term than saying &quot;I need a raise, heroin isn't cheap you know.&quot;<br />
<br />
If a raise won't stop you from seriously looking for a job it's somewhat dishonest to ask but if you end up working that job for years still looking for another job it's a lot of money you could be leaving on the table.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				In the event that I am offered the new position, how or at what point do you think I should tell my current employer that I'm planning to leave?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Assuming you can get your boss to a restuarant without him/her thinking sexual harassment or knowing this must mean he's (threatening) quitting, in which case you're effectively dropping the bomb at the office anyways you want to make quitting more memorable than &quot;My last day is xxx, thanks for the training and experience and I've really enjoyed working with you.&quot;<br />
<br />
First stress the factors beyond your boss' control as to why you are leaving.  I don't want to find out in 10 years that I would have really preferred to be doing xxxx instead.  Sometimes just the idea of working the same job for 20 years just scares me, I need change more than anything.<br />
<br />
Next bring up money, but then double back and repeat that it's not the most important thing because taking his best/matching offer at this point is most likely a really bad long term plan.  It's very likely your boss would switch companies if a substansial raise was involved, through all the horse shit you better bring up the one thing you are sure your boss will understand and accept.<br />
<br />
Finally, get in one last no holds barred ass kissing about how wonderful working for them has been and how if they got a job at the new company it would be so incredible and how one day you hope to do as good a job as they are but you're still years away from that kind of opportunity.  Excuse yourself to the bathroom and mumble something about emotional and get the laughter out in the privacy of a stall instead of in their face and then return, complete the meal and pick up the cheque.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
