	</table>
</div><br />
Nope. <br />
<br />
Trust is very important in business, unless you're running a monopoly and can afford to screw over your business partners every other week.<br />
<br />
While you're still a peon, you want to seem loyal to protect your own long term interests. If your bosses don't trust you to be loyal, you get a ticket to the magical land of perpetual middle management (at best).<br />
<br />
If you want a higher pay, move to a new job or negotiate a better pay with your current employers. Don't use a new job offer as leverage for a pay raise. Don't even mention the fact that you've been applying to other jobs. Make it seem like you went to them first, before the thought of changing jobs ever entered your mind.<br />
<br />
If I were your boss, and you're blackmailing me for higher pay with the old &quot;Company X is offering me THIS much money!!!!&quot; routine, I'd offer just enough to make you stay (assuming you're good at what you do), and immediately make sure that someone else can do your job in the eventuality that you leave.<br />
<br />
You've just become redundant. You won't be promoted ahead of anyone, and you'll be on the list if your company ever decides to streamline operations.<br />
<br />
That's just me though. Your boss might be more forgiving. Or forgetful.</div>
