		<!-- message -->
		<div>There are two parts to this. The first part is that recently I asked for a raise, but knowing the company I work for, they will give me, but make it a salaried position. I worked a lot of overtime recently, we are talking 80 -90 work week. If they agree to give me a raise and tie it to a salaried position, then I would decline it. The expectation from them would be for me to go back to the 80 hour weeks and I wouldn't get any further compensation for it. <br />
<br />
The reason I said all of that is because many companies will look at it as a cost benefit to them. They put you on salary and then drop a ton of work on you so you have to work a lot more hours. They know how much work is coming down the road. <br />
<br />
How soon do you tell your boss if you get another job? Right away. Very few companies these days feel any loyalty to their employees. From what Cam says here, he does take care of his, but I think that type of business owner is rare. If your company could find someone to do your job at an equal level and pay them less money, you would be out the door quickly. Remember the old saying, it's not personal, it's business. Well you need to think of that in your own terms. It's not personal, it's business and you are making a business decision that's right for you. <br />
<br />
Sorry if it sounds jaded, but it's real world.<br />
<br />
Dest</div>
