				</div>
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Now rationally, I would think that when you promote someone from hourly to salary, you look at the job they currently do, the hours worked and expected in the future, and make sure that a decent amount of OT is covered in the initial raise. It would be silly to give someone a &quot;promotion,&quot; but in practice pay them less. But that's what happened to me. The raise I got was worth about 2 hours per week of overtime, but I averaged double that in 2004, and that was with some significant periods of downtime with no OT at all. Jan and Feb are busy months, but I can see my longterm workload still increasing, and see little chance that I'll actually work less next year. In fact I don't really want to work less, I do like my job, and more work generally means better job security.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
You will very rarely see an increase of pay when you get promoted from hourly to salary. I actually made more money when I was hourly then I am currently while on salary, and that was over a year ago. The 15 days of paid vacation time is nice I guess though when I wasn't getting vacation days when paid by the hour, and sick days are paid on salary while they are not when hourly. I never did overtime anyways since my job doesn't require such a thing. I prefer salary to be honest as your pay isn't affected by unforseen events like being sick.<br />
<br />
I'd suggest to go and ask for more compensation for your past overtime hours. In the end, you will still make less then what you made hourly, but you can at least cover the gap a bit.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
