	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Lascaris</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">It's very common when I transition someone from hourly to salary that they see a short term decrease in pay.  I've had several people refuse promotions for this reason.  I try to point out that the people in this situation typically are near thier top end earning potential as an hourly and the long term compensation potential of being salaried are worth the short term drop but some choose not to listen.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Or they choose not to trust.  If people can't see for themselves how the system is supposed to benefit them they won't take the risk.  I would definitely not turn down a promotion, but words are cheap unless written down in legalese and signed, and explanations about vague future earnings potential don't mean a whole lot without action to back it up.  <br />
<br />
Perhaps more significantly in my case, the job is one that I could be making significantly more for at a different company, and my company would probably pay me more for if I hadn't started in the hourly position.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				The rule of thumb at every place I've ever worked is to base the salary on people transitioning from hourly on their base, i.e. without unscheduled OT, wages adjusted for equity with others within their new pay grade.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>And, frankly, that is a terrible way to do it.  A person moving into a new position should be made an offer based on the position and their qualifications, not how much they were making before.  To do otherwise is treating the employee as a number, which is not the sort of thing that will encourage people to continue working for advancement.<br />
<br />
The message this sends to me is that no matter what I do, I can look forward to miniscule raises the rest of my life at the company, with the _chance_ that I might someday break into upper management and get a significant increase.  I'm not going to wait 10 years for them to reward my effort, when another company is offering it to me now, no matter what sweet nothings they whisper into my ear.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
